  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dd1d04fa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Identify differentially accessible regions\n",
    "\n",
    "This tutorial assumes you have read the [Standard Pipeline](https://kzhang.org/SnapATAC2/tutorials/pbmc.html) tutorial and have finished preprocessing, clustering and cell annotations."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "a6207641",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "'2.3.0.dev4'"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 1,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import snapatac2 as snap\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import polars as pl\n",
    "\n",
    "snap.__version__"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "255a5200",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "First let's load the previously processed h5ad file."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "70059f17",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Updating file 'atac_pbmc_5k_annotated.h5ad' from 'https://osf.io/download/rvwhf/' to '/home/kaizhang/.cache/snapatac2'.\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "AnnData object with n_obs x n_vars = 4436 x 6062095 backed at '/home/kaizhang/.cache/snapatac2/atac_pbmc_5k_annotated.h5ad'\n",
       "    obs: 'tsse', 'n_fragment', 'frac_dup', 'frac_mito', 'doublet_probability', 'doublet_score', 'leiden', 'cell_type'\n",
       "    var: 'count', 'selected'\n",
       "    uns: 'spectral_eigenvalue', 'cell_type_colors', 'reference_sequences', 'leiden_colors', 'scrublet_sim_doublet_score'\n",
       "    obsm: 'X_spectral', 'X_umap', 'insertion'\n",
       "    obsp: 'distances'"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 2,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "data = snap.read(snap.datasets.pbmc5k(type=\"annotated_h5ad\"))\n",
    "data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "42f823f0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {

      ]

     "execution_count": 3,

     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "snap.pl.umap(data, color='cell_type', width=700, interactive=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8d3be27b-bae3-4c85-8000-9142123e32e2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Peak calling at the cluster-level\n",
    "\n",
    "An important goal of single-cell ATAC-seq analysis is to identify genomic regions that are enriched with TN5 insertions, or open chromatin regions. Using `snap.tl.call_peaks`, we can easily identify open chromatin regions in different cell populations stratified by provided group information."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "27b23412",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "2023-04-13 14:49:04 - INFO - Exporting data...\n",
      "2023-04-13 14:54:33 - INFO - Calling peaks for 11 groups ...\n",
      "2023-04-13 15:09:47 - INFO - Merging peaks...\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "CPU times: user 5min 50s, sys: 11.6 s, total: 6min 2s\n",
      "Wall time: 20min 45s\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "%%time\n",
    "snap.tl.call_peaks(data, groupby='cell_type')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5cc81b0e-19bb-4b49-910b-cf1447144764",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "`snap.tl.call_peaks` first calls peaks for individual groups and then merges overlapping peaks to create a list of fix-width non-overlapping peaks. The intermediate results are discarded by default but can be saved using the `out_dir` parameter.\n",
    "\n",
    "Results of peak calling are stored in `data.uns['peaks']` as a dataframe. Rows are merged peaks, and columns are cell clusters. Boolean values in the dataframe indicate whether a peak is present in a given cell cluster."
   ]
  },

  {

   "id": "d23b2f40",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, with the peak list, we can create a cell by peak matrix by `snap.pp.make_peak_matrix`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "dc0cb7a8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {

    {

   ],
   "source": [
    "%%time\n",

    "peak_mat"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "754989ea",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finding marker regions\n",
    "---------------------------\n",
    "\n",
    "In this section, we are going to use a quick-and-dirty method to identify marker regions for each cell type. The `tl.marker_regions` function aggregates signal across cells and utilizes z-scores to identify specifically enriched peaks."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "90f98754",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "/projects/ps-renlab2/kai/dev/snapatac2/snapatac2-python/snapatac2/tools/_misc.py:82: FutureWarning:\n",
      "\n",
      "X.dtype being converted to np.float32 from float64. In the next version of anndata (0.9) conversion will not be automatic. Pass dtype explicitly to avoid this warning. Pass `AnnData(X, dtype=X.dtype, ...)` to get the future behavour.\n",
      "\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "CPU times: user 6.56 s, sys: 499 ms, total: 7.06 s\n",
      "Wall time: 7.05 s\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "%%time\n",
    "marker_peaks = snap.tl.marker_regions(peak_mat, groupby='cell_type', pvalue=0.01)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "7b908ecc",
   "metadata": {},

     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "snap.pl.regions(peak_mat, groupby='cell_type', peaks=marker_peaks, interactive=False)"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "73c18482",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Regression-based differential test\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "The `tl.marker_regions` above does not consider the variations across cells. To fully utilize the single-cell information, we can apply regression-based differential test method. First, Let's select the peaks that are either present in naive B cells or memory B cells."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "cd204b74",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "group1 = \"Naive/Intermediate B\"\n",
    "group2 = \"Memory B\"\n",
    "naive_B = data.obs['cell_type'] == group1\n",
    "memory_B = data.obs['cell_type'] == group2\n",
    "peaks_selected = np.logical_or(\n",
    "    data.uns[\"peaks\"][group1].to_numpy(),\n",
    "    data.uns[\"peaks\"][group2].to_numpy(),\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2be1314e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Perform differential test using `tl.diff_test`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "2f1d6a8b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "2023-04-13 15:16:48 - INFO - Input contains 107629 features, now perform filtering with 'min_log_fc = 0.25' and 'min_pct = 0.05' ...\n",
      "2023-04-13 15:17:02 - INFO - Testing 33352 features ...\n",
      "100%|| 33352/33352 [05:01<00:00, 110.59it/s]\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "CPU times: user 5min 16s, sys: 2.17 s, total: 5min 18s\n",
      "Wall time: 5min 18s\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "%%time\n",
    "diff_peaks = snap.tl.diff_test(\n",
    "    peak_mat,\n",
    "    cell_group1=naive_B,\n",
    "    cell_group2=memory_B,\n",
    "    features=peaks_selected,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "abaf7f98",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In the next example we are going to identify peaks that are accessible in memory B cells but not in the rest of cells. One way of doing this is to select random cells from each cluster to form the background, and then perform test between memory B cells and the background.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we randomly select 50 cells from other cell clusters, and set the `direction = \"positive\"` because we are interested in peaks that are more accessible in memory B cells."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "f48547ae",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "barcodes = np.array(data.obs_names)\n",
    "background = []\n",
    "for i in np.unique(data.obs['leiden']):\n",
    "    if i != group2:\n",
    "        cells = np.random.choice(\n",
    "            barcodes[data.obs['leiden'] == i],\n",
    "            size = 50,\n",
    "            replace = False,\n",
    "        )\n",
    "        background.append(cells)\n",
    "background = np.concatenate(background)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "e87b733f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",

      "100%|| 18700/18700 [03:11<00:00, 97.69it/s]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "diff_peaks = snap.tl.diff_test(\n",
    "    peak_mat,\n",
    "    cell_group1 = memory_B,\n",
    "    cell_group2 = background,\n",
    "    features = data.uns[\"peaks\"][group2].to_numpy(),\n",
    "    direction = \"positive\",\n",
    ")"
   ]
